<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900423-0031</DOCNO><DOCID>900423-0031.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Recognition Equipment Inc.:   Two Former Insurers Sued   For Liability Cases' Costs</HL><DATE>04/23/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4</SO><CO>   REC STPL</CO><LP>   Recognition Equipment Inc., Dallas, said it sued twoformer insurance carriers in state district court, seeking torecover more than $9 million under its directors' andofficers' liability insurance policies.   The maker of data management equipment filed the action inthe Dallas court against Harbor Insurance Co., which was itsprimary carrier, and St. Paul Surplus Lines Insurance Co. inthe bid to collect on costs and expenses related to defendingRecognition and two former executives in criminal and civillawsuits. Harbor, Los Angeles, is a unit of ContinentalCorp., a New York-based insurance holding company. St. PaulSurplus Lines is a unit of St. Paul Cos., a St. Paul, Minn.,insurer. Both insurance policies expired last year,Recognition said.</LP><TEXT>   The company and its two former executives were acquittedlast November of charges that they tried to manipulate theaward of U.S. Postal Service contracts for mail-sortingequipment. Recognition said that civil suits against thecompany relating to the criminal charges are pending, andthat its total claims against the insurance companies forthose lawsuits and others could exceed $10 million.</TEXT></DOC>